Tunnel construction collapse refers to the phenomenon that occurs after the excavation of a tunnel when there is a lack of advanced support during construction, a failure to timely implement initial support, or when the parameters for initial support are inadequately adjusted based on the actual excavated rock mass classification, leading to significant deformation and loss of stability of the surrounding rock. This can also happen when the surrounding rock and initial support undergo deformation to a degree that results in the failure of the initial support, causing the surrounding rock to fall. 

Collapse-related disaster structures refer to geological features that, due to tunnel excavation, experience a loss of self-stabilizing capacity under the influence of gravitational stress above the two sidewall bases, or exhibit poor self-stabilization capabilities due to surrounding rock deformation, or reach a sufficient level of water absorption and expansion to lose self-stability, resulting in the formation of falling geological entities. 

Collapse-related disaster structures include: 
(1) Soil surrounding rock; 
(2) Soft rock; 
(3) Expansive rock; 
(4) Semi-consolidated rock; 
(5) Fractured rock masses composed of thinly layered rocks and shale; 
(6) Fractured rock bodies in non-cemented fault zones; 
(7) Fractured rock masses in layer-parallel displacement zones; 
(8) Fractured rock bodies in areas of dense joint development; 
(9) Rock masses filled with karst materials; 
(10) Loose accumulations in abandoned mine tunnels.
